echo '<div class="mk-prose">';
echo '<p class="mk-muted" style="margin-top:0;">The transatlantic slave trade, internal African slavery systems, the Igbo experience, and abolition.</p>';
echo '<h2>The Scale of the Crime</h2>';
echo '<p>Between 1500 and 1900, approximately 12.5 million Africans were captured, transported across the Atlantic, and enslaved in the Americas. Of these, an estimated 10.7 million survived the Middle Passage. They and their descendants built the economies of Brazil, the Caribbean, and the American South. The wealth generated by their forced labor funded the industrial revolution in Britain, France, and the United States.</p>';
echo '<p>The Bight of Biafra — the stretch of Atlantic coast corresponding to modern southeastern Nigeria — was one of the most active slaving zones in the entire Atlantic system. Approximately 1.6 million enslaved people were exported from this region, the vast majority of them Igbo. This makes the Igbo one of the largest single-language groups in the African diaspora.</p>';
echo '<h2>How Igbo People Were Enslaved</h2>';
echo '<p>Igbo people were enslaved through multiple mechanisms. Wars between communities produced captives who could be sold. The Aro trading network — centered on the Aro Chukwu oracle at Arochukwu — operated a sophisticated system in which the oracle\'s "judgments" produced enslaved people who were channeled to coastal ports. Kidnapping was also widespread. Debt and punishment within Igbo society itself could result in enslavement, though internal Igbo slavery was typically different in character from the chattel slavery of the Atlantic system.</p>';
echo '<h2>The Igbo Diaspora in the Americas</h2>';
echo '<p>Igbo people enslaved in the Americas left traces that survive to this day. In Jamaica, the "Ibo Landing" tradition — the story of Igbo captives who drowned themselves rather than accept enslavement — became a powerful symbol of resistance. In South Carolina and Virginia, Igbo cultural influences can be traced in place names, folk traditions, and community practices. The Gullah people of the Sea Islands preserve cultural memories of West African origin that include Igbo elements.</p>';
echo '<h2>Abolition and Its Limits</h2>';
echo '<p>Britain abolished the slave trade in 1807 and slavery in its colonies in 1833. The United States abolished slavery in 1865. These legal abolitions did not end the consequences of slavery — the wealth extracted from enslaved labor funded the industrialization of the West, while the communities that produced the enslaved remained impoverished and colonized. The descendants of enslaved people in the Americas continue to bear the structural consequences of slavery in systems of racial inequality that persist to the present day.</p>';
echo '<h2>Internal African Slavery</h2>';
echo '<p>Slavery existed within African societies before and after the Atlantic trade — and the Atlantic trade intensified internal slavery by creating external demand. Within Igbo society, "ohu" (slaves) and "osu" (shrine slaves) occupied the lowest social positions. The osu system — in which individuals and their descendants were dedicated to deities and permanently excluded from mainstream society — survived long after the abolition of the Atlantic trade and persists in attenuated form in some Igbo communities today, a source of significant social stigma and ongoing debate.</p>';
